ajeffrey.teaching.util.list

Interface Iterator


  • public interface Iterator
    An iterator over a collection. This is an implementation of the Iterator pattern from the `Gang of Four' book. It is a simplified version of the Java Iterator interface, and does not support deletion. Collections can return Iterator objects to iterate over them, for example: 
       List l = ...;
   for (Iterator i = l.iterator (); i.hasNext ();) {
     Object next = i.next ();
     ...
   }
    If the underlying list is modified while the iterator is being used, one of two things may happen:
    • A IteratorModificationException may be thrown.
    • The iterator will iterate over the elements in the original list, not over the elements in the new list.
    See Lea for a discussion of concurrent updates to collections.
    Version:
    1.0.1
    Author:
    Alan Jeffrey
